Seed 10 external domain knowledge entries for this subpersona:

1. Title: Hydropower projects are capital intensive
Topic: capex_benchmarks
Text: Hydroelectric projects typically require high upfront capital expenditure due to civil infrastructure, electro-mechanical equipment, and transmission interconnection. Financial viability is therefore highly sensitive to construction cost discipline and financing structure.
Source name: International Energy Agency
Document title: Technology Roadmap - Hydropower

2. Title: Cost overruns materially affect project returns
Topic: cost_overrun_risk
Text: Hydropower projects are vulnerable to cost overruns caused by geological uncertainty, contractor underperformance, inflation in materials, and delays in civil works. Because capital is deployed early, overruns can materially reduce project returns and debt capacity.
Source name: World Bank
Document title: Hydropower Project Preparation Guidance

3. Title: Revenue depends on dependable generation, not headline output
Topic: tariff_revenue
Text: Revenue forecasts for hydroelectric assets should be based on dependable generation under realistic hydrological conditions rather than optimistic annual averages. Overstated generation assumptions can significantly distort projected returns.
Source name: International Hydropower Association
Document title: Hydropower Sustainability Standard

4. Title: Hydrology variability creates financial fragility
Topic: hydrology_sensitivity
Text: Changes in river flow directly affect generation output and therefore project revenue. Financial models should test dry-season performance, drought scenarios, and multi-year variability rather than relying only on average historical flow.
Source name: International Energy Agency
Document title: Technology Roadmap - Hydropower

5. Title: Long development cycles delay value realization
Topic: time_to_value
Text: Hydroelectric projects often require lengthy development timelines covering site studies, permitting, financing, construction, commissioning, and grid connection. This delays cash flow generation and reduces near-term capital efficiency.
Source name: World Bank
Document title: Hydropower Project Cycle Reference

6. Title: Grid connection costs can materially alter economics
Topic: grid_connection_cost
Text: In remote hydroelectric projects, transmission and interconnection costs can form a significant share of total project cost. Financial assessment should test whether the project remains attractive after realistic power evacuation costs are included.
Source name: International Energy Agency
Document title: Hydropower Technology Roadmap

7. Title: Tariff assumptions should be stress-tested
Topic: tariff_revenue
Text: Project economics depend heavily on offtake structure, tariff certainty, and dispatch assumptions. Financial evaluation should test downside cases where pricing, offtake terms, or utilization differ from base case expectations.
Source name: World Bank
Document title: Infrastructure Finance Guidance

8. Title: Delay risk compounds financing burden
Topic: construction_delay_impact
Text: Construction delays increase interest during construction, defer revenue, and can trigger covenant or refinancing pressure. Hydro projects are particularly exposed because revenue realization typically begins only after substantial capital deployment.
Source name: World Bank
Document title: Hydropower Development and Financing Notes

9. Title: Opex is usually lower than thermal generation but not negligible
Topic: opex_profile
Text: Hydropower plants often have relatively low operating costs once commissioned, but maintenance of turbines, generators, dam infrastructure, sediment handling systems, and monitoring equipment must still be reflected in long-term financial models.
Source name: U.S. Department of Energy
Document title: Hydropower Basics

10. Title: Financing resilience depends on assumption robustness
Topic: debt_service_risk
Text: The ability of a hydroelectric project to support debt depends on how robust cash flows remain under downside scenarios such as lower-than-expected generation, delayed commissioning, higher capex, and extended outages.
Source name: World Bank
Document title: Infrastructure Project Finance Notes

